00:43:50.719 --> 00:43:55.760
so you match up the instrument that each Beatle played with, you know, what song they wrote,

00:43:56.560 --> 00:44:02.560
you can do that with a left join. What left join does is it takes the names of two data frames,

00:44:02.560 --> 00:44:06.800
and then it takes some joining criteria. These would be the name or names of columns

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:14.320
that both data sets share. And then what it will do is it'll go through the second data frame,

00:44:14.320 --> 00:44:18.959
find the pieces of information that apply to rows in the first data frame, and add them where they

00:44:18.959 --> 00:44:22.879
belong in that data frame. So order is not preserved. The second data frame's order is

00:44:22.879 --> 00:44:27.040
not preserved. First data frame, yes, that is preserved. But things are moved around

00:44:27.040 --> 00:44:31.679
to supply a play column that actually makes sense with your data frame. And at the end,

00:44:31.679 --> 00:44:38.239
you have rows in your output that describe a unified observation. John both wrote Across

00:44:38.239 --> 00:44:43.600
the Universe and played guitar. Guitar had to appear twice, because John's also in the second

00:44:43.600 --> 00:44:48.239
row, and so it appears twice. There's no information about this last row, Buddy Holly,

00:44:48.239 --> 00:44:52.879
who made Peggy Sue. So for the plays column, that gets an NA. There's nothing we could put there.

