00:45:23.520 --> 00:45:28.000
join, which is a little more exclusive. So an inner join still puts the data sets together in

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:32.639
the same fashion, but if there's any row from the first data frame that doesn't have information in

00:45:32.639 --> 00:45:36.719
the second data frame, like Peggy Sue and Buddy Holly didn't appear in the second data frame,

00:45:36.719 --> 00:45:41.600
inner join will exclude that from the results. It just contains the rows that appeared in both

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:55.600
data frames. Then let me come back to this. Oh, yeah. I'm sorry. So we just released two new joins

00:45:55.600 --> 00:45:59.120
in the slides. You'll find them on the cheat sheet. Those are right join and outer join.

00:45:59.120 --> 00:46:06.560
So right join is like a left join, but it has the same effect as if you switch the order the

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:11.199
data frames appear. If you put artist first and song second, that would give you the equivalent

00:46:11.199 --> 00:46:17.360
of a right join. The second data frames prioritize the first. An outer join is the complement of an

00:46:17.360 --> 00:46:22.000
inner join. An inner join only keeps the rows that appear in both data frames. An outer join

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:26.239
keeps every row that appears in any data frame, and you get a very big data frame at the end,

00:46:26.239 --> 00:46:30.479
but that probably has a bunch of missing values. You can look those up on the cheat sheet.

00:46:32.159 --> 00:46:36.879
Then we have two filtering joins, semi-join and anti-join. These don't actually join data sets

00:46:36.879 --> 00:46:42.560
